{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782362891367,"sessionID":"ses_102e4b379ffemg20qTMGqq4dM7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_KIgh3Ok3WsiceDAiWuZew9uI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md"},"output":"<path>D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Agent Protocol\n2: \n3: This protocol is the stable instruction source for `opencode-cj` sessions in the Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie workflow. Human operators and orchestration scripts may reference this file from generated prompts.\n4: \n5: ## 1. Role\n6: \n7: You are the translation agent for an Android Kotlin app to HarmonyOS Cangjie app migration.\n8: \n9: You perform the actual target-project source translation and target-project source fixes. You preserve the source app's user-visible behavior while adapting implementation, resources, data flow, state management, and build configuration to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n10: \n11: ## 2. Authority Boundaries\n12: \n13: - You may modify files under `<target-project>/`.\n14: - You may create or update `plan.md` and strict `plan.json` during planning.\n15: - Do not modify `<source-project>/`.\n16: - Do not modify `translation-inputs/` except when a prompt explicitly asks you to write a small deferred note there.\n17: - Do not modify `translation-records/`.\n18: - Do not modify workflow scripts, analyzer code, build-gate scripts, or this protocol unless the user explicitly asks for toolchain work.\n19: - Do not replace the orchestration flow with a separate translator, analyzer, or build system.\n20: - Do not assume app-specific names from previous migrations.\n21: \n22: ## 3. Required Inputs\n23: \n24: Read the relevant files before making decisions:\n25: \n26: - `task-planning.md`\n27: - `plan.md`\n28: - `plan.json`\n29: - `translation-inputs/preflight-report.md`\n30: - `translation-inputs/sdk-report.json`\n31: - `translation-inputs/skills-report.md`\n32: - `translation-inputs/plan-seed.md` and `translation-inputs/plan-seed.json` when present\n33: - `translation-inputs/source-feature-survey.md`\n34: - `translation-inputs/resource-coverage-report.md`\n35: - `translation-inputs/coverage-gap-report.md`\n36: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/gradle-model.json`\n37: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/analysis.json`\n38: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/locations.json`\n39: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/planning-note.md`\n40: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/manifest-summary.json`\n41: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/resource-map.json`\n42: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/screen-map.json`\n43: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/view-bindings.json`\n44: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/layout-tree.json`\n45: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/drawable-semantics.json`\n46: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/adapter-map.json`\n47: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/behavior-spec.md`\n48: - `X2Cangjie/docs/harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md`\n49: - The current phase's `build-report.md`, if fixing a build blocker.\n50: - The current phase's `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt`, if fixing a build blocker.\n51: \n52: If an input is missing, continue only when the missing input is not essential for the requested step. Report the gap.\n53: \n54: `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/planning-note.md` may report multiple Kotlin or Java source roots. Treat that as the normal multi-module case and use the combined `analysis.json` plus source files as the structural reference for all modules.\n55: \n56: If multi-module analysis failed before translation planning because the analyzer protocol probe failed, do not work around it in the target project. Ask the operator to rebuild the analyzer instead of proceeding from partial static inputs.\n57: \n58: ## 3.1 Static Analysis Scope\n59: \n60: Treat `translation-inputs/` as structured planning evidence and indexes, not as a complete source of truth. Do not assume a source feature is absent only because it is missing from generated analysis.\n61: \n62: Use `source-feature-survey.md`, `resource-coverage-report.md`, and `coverage-gap-report.md` as a coverage baseline. Their purpose is to reduce functional gaps and unexplained code-scale gaps. Do not mechanically match source LoC; instead, map current-phase critical/high source files, resources, tests, and platform integrations to target implementation, supplemental tests, or explicit deferred items with source evidence and reason.\n63: \n64: For current-phase decisions:\n65: \n66: - Use structured inputs first to locate relevant source screens, composables, resources, data paths, settings/preferences, callbacks, navigation, persistence, Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, and state-refresh behavior.\n67: - If behavior, resources, bindings, navigation, persistence, or state refresh semantics are unclear, inspect the minimal relevant source project files.\n68: - If source code contradicts or supplements generated analysis, follow the source code.\n69: - Report the analysis gap so later phases do not inherit a false assumption.\n70: \n71: ## 3.2 Kotlin-Specific Behavior Evidence\n72: \n73: When the source app uses Jetpack Compose, inspect composables, remembered state, state hoisting, callbacks, navigation routes, LazyColumn/LazyRow contents, dialogs, bottom bars, and event handlers before planning target files.\n74: \n75: When the source app uses XML/ViewBinding, inspect Activity/Fragment lifecycle flow, adapters, RecyclerView/ListView refresh behavior, click listeners, validation, and navigation before planning target files.\n76: \n77: When the source app uses ViewModel, StateFlow, LiveData, coroutine, repository, Room, Retrofit, Firebase, DataStore, or SharedPreferences, preserve the user-visible observable behavior even if the translated implementation uses local HarmonyOS-compatible abstractions.\n78: \n79: ## 4. Planning Session Requirements\n80: \n81: In a planning session, generate or update:\n82: \n83: - `plan.md`\n84: - `plan.json`\n85: \n86: `plan.md` must define the migration phases, phase goals, phase dependencies, build gates, review points, deferred items, and behavior risks.\n87: \n88: `plan.json` must be strict JSON and cover:\n89: \n90: - `files`: target files, source references, top-level definitions, and translation guidelines.\n91: - `assets`: strings, images, colors, layouts, styles, vectors, animations, menus, and resource adaptation rules.\n92: - `dependencies`: third-party dependencies and their HarmonyOS Cangjie replacement strategy.\n93: - `tests`: existing source tests to migrate, generated tests for uncovered core behavior, supplemental tests for shallow source coverage, and test commands or deferred validation.\n94: - `phases`: canonical phase identifiers, target scope, required inputs, expected files, implementation groups, and gate criteria.\n95: - `deferred`: known incomplete items, reason, owner phase, and validation needed.\n96: \n97: Planning must explicitly map:\n98: \n99: - `plan-seed` source units, callable function/composable/event-handler contracts, UI contracts, data contracts, resource contracts, platform capability contracts, structure risks, and analysis gaps to phases and implementation groups.\n100: - Kotlin classes, Android Activities, Fragments, ViewModels, repositories, Compose composables, XML/ViewBinding screens, adapters, listeners, callbacks, StateFlow/LiveData observers, and coroutine-driven side effects.\n101: - Android resources and layouts to HarmonyOS resources and ArkUI builders.\n102: - Persistence, backend SDKs, local storage, network APIs, and CRUD/data-flow behavior.\n103: - UI state, observable data, navigation, validation, error messages, and refresh semantics.\n104: - Source tests and project-specific verification assets to target tests or target-side validation cases.\n105: \n106: Each implementation group in `plan.json` should include stable `groupId`, `title`, `groupType`, `priority`, `sourcePaths`, source function/composable or callable contract references when available, `featureIds`, `resourceInputs`, `platformCapabilityIds`, UI/data contract references or hints, `expectedTargetDomains`, `requiredBehaviors`, `riskHints`, and `acceptanceEvidence`. Treat `plan-seed` as planning evidence, not a complete source of truth; inspect source files when behavior is unclear or when source code contradicts static analysis, and record `analysisGaps` or `sourceOverrides` instead of silently dropping behavior.\n107: \n108: Do not implement the migration during a planning-only session unless the human prompt explicitly authorizes it.\n109: \n110: ## 5. Build Phase Rules\n111: \n112: For every phase:\n113: \n114: - Re-read `task-planning.md`, `plan.md`, and `plan.json`.\n115: - Read the structured analysis inputs relevant to this phase.\n116: - Work only on the current phase's scope unless a small prerequisite fix is required.\n117: - Keep source-file structure understandable; do not collapse the app into one large file.\n118: - Prefer HarmonyOS Cangjie idioms and the checklist over Android or ArkTS assumptions.\n119: - Do not leave direct Android SDK, Firebase SDK, or unavailable third-party library references in target Cangjie code unless explicitly deferred with a replacement plan.\n120: - Migrate source tests relevant to the current phase. If source tests are absent or too shallow for current phase behavior, add focused target-side tests for translated business, data, state, validation, refresh, Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, or persistence logic.\n121: - Prefer runnable target-project tests. If a behavior cannot be automated with the available template/SDK in this phase, keep the code testable and record the deferred validation path.\n122: - After edits, review the target project against `plan.md` and `plan.json`.\n123: - If `apply_patch` fails, read back affected files before retrying.\n124: - If a long session is interrupted, inspect the current filesystem state before continuing.\n125: \n126: ## 6. Build Blocker Fix Rules\n127: \n128: When fixing a build blocker:\n129: \n130: - Read `build-report.md`.\n131: - Read `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt`.\n132: - Fix the first visible blocker or the smallest coherent blocker class.\n133: - Do not perform unrelated redesigns.\n134: - Do not advance to a new phase.\n135: - Preserve phase intent and existing completed work.\n136: - Do not delete, disable, or weaken migrated/generated tests merely to make the build pass. Fix the implementation or record an explicit deferred test limitation when necessary.\n137: - After fixing, state which blocker was addressed and what still needs a build gate rerun.\n138: \n139: ## 7. Phase-End Checks\n140: \n141: At the end of a phase:\n142: \n143: - Check whether current target files contradict `plan.md` or `plan.json`.\n144: - Check whether the phase introduced files or code not needed by current or later phases.\n145: - Check whether UI state transitions and data refresh paths required by this phase are represented.\n146: - Check whether resources referenced by code exist in the target resource tree.\n147: - Check whether current-phase tests were migrated, generated, supplemented, run when possible, or explicitly deferred.\n148: - Check whether deferred state-machine, data-flow, backend, runtime, or resource gaps are recorded.\n149: \n150: ## 8. Prompt Templates\n151: \n152: ### Planning Session Template\n153: \n154: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a planning session:\n155: \n156: ```text\n157: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n158: Read and follow task-planning.md: <task-planning>.\n159: This is a planning session only.\n160: Generate or update <plan.md> and <plan.json>.\n161: Use translation-inputs as structured planning evidence.\n162: Do not modify source project files.\n163: Do not modify translation-records or workflow scripts.\n164: Report changed files, commands run, plan coverage, missing inputs, and deferred risks.\n165: ```\n166: \n167: ### Phase Session Template\n168: \n169: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a phase session:\n170: \n171: ```text\n172: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n173: Read task-planning.md, plan.md, and plan.json before editing.\n174: Start only phase <phase>.\n175: Use relevant translation-inputs and the HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist.\n176: Modify only the target project files needed for this phase.\n177: Do not skip phase-end checks.\n178: Report changed files, commands run, build status if known, plan changes, deferred issues, and next recommended action.\n179: ```\n180: \n181: ### Build Blocker Template\n182: \n183: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a build-blocker fix session:\n184: \n185: ```text\n186: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n187: Read the build blocker prompt: <opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt>.\n188: Read the build report before editing.\n189: Fix only the current phase's build blocker or smallest coherent blocker class.\n190: Do not perform unrelated refactors.\n191: Report changed files, commands run, blocker addressed, remaining blockers, deferred issues, and next recommended action.\n192: ```\n193: \n194: ## 9. Required Final Response Format\n195: \n196: End every session with:\n197: \n198: ```text\n199: Changed files:\n200: - <path>: <what changed>\n201: \n202: Commands run:\n203: - <command or \"none\">\n204: \n205: Build result:\n206: - <PASS/FAIL/NOT RUN/UNKNOWN and report path if available>\n207: \n208: Plan changes:\n209: - <plan updates or \"none\">\n210: \n211: Deferred issues:\n212: - <issue, owner phase, validation needed, or \"none\">\n213: \n214: Next recommended action:\n215: - <one concrete next step>\n216: ```\n\n(End of file - total 216 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Agent Protocol\n\nThis protocol is the stable instruction source for `opencode-cj` sessions in the Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie workflow. Human operators and orchestration scripts may reference this file from generated prompts.\n\n## 1. Role\n\nYou are the translation agent for an Android Kotlin app to HarmonyOS Cangjie app migration.\n\nYou perform the actual target-project source translation and target-project source fixes. You preserve the source app's user-visible behavior while adapting implementation, resources, data flow, state management, and build configuration to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n\n## 2. Authority Boundaries\n\n- You may modify files under `<target-project>/`.\n- You may create or update `plan.md` and strict `plan.json` during planning.\n- Do not modify `<source-project>/`.\n- Do not modify `translation-inputs/` except when a prompt explicitly asks you to write a small deferred note there.\n- Do not modify `translation-records/`.\n- Do not modify workflow scripts, analyzer code, build-gate scripts, or this protocol unless the user explicitly asks for toolchain work.\n- Do not replace the orchestration flow with a separate translator, analyzer, or build system.\n- Do not assume app-specific names from previous migrations.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"..\\..\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md","time":{"start":1782362891351,"end":1782362891366}},"id":"prt_efd1b6434001yef6LA5MPkNpIk","sessionID":"ses_102e4b379ffemg20qTMGqq4dM7","messageID":"msg_efd1b4d69001W4VyVM7ZOg17w7"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782362891382,"sessionID":"ses_102e4b379ffemg20qTMGqq4dM7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_i3RgWMcgkAV2m7WriU4XUhnC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\task-planning.md"},"output":"<path>D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\task-planning.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Translation Plan\n2: \n3: ## Goal\n4: \n5: Translate the Android Kotlin project in `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike` into a HarmonyOS Cangjie project rooted at `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`, preserving main features, screen flow, resources, state changes, data behavior, tests, and user-visible side effects while adapting implementation to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n6: \n7: ## Paths\n8: \n9: - App name: `Foodike`\n10: - Source kind: `kotlin`\n11: - Translation workspace: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike`\n12: - Workspace standing instructions: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\AGENTS.md`\n13: - Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n14: - Target HarmonyOS Cangjie project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n15: - Translation inputs: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs`\n16: - Translation records: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-records`\n17: - Agent protocol: `D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md`\n18: - HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist: `D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\docs\\harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md`\n19: \n20: ## Role Split\n21: \n22: - The source project is read-only behavior evidence.\n23: - The target project is the only application source tree that `opencode-cj` may modify.\n24: - `translation-inputs/` may contain generated reports, static analysis from separate Kotlin/Android analysis tools and Gradle metadata export, mapcir reference artifacts, and the agent-maintained `source-coverage-matrix.json/md` and `platform-capability-check.json/md`. Treat generated reports as read-only planning evidence; update only the source coverage matrix and platform capability check when recording migration coverage status.\n25: - The mapcir output, when present, is a deterministic bootstrap/reference artifact. Use it for project structure, resources, dependencies, and initial skeleton only. Do not treat generated placeholders as final business logic.\n26: - The workflow scripts orchestrate preparation and validation only; `opencode-cj` performs semantic translation and build repair.\n27: \n28: ## Structured Inputs\n29: \n30: Always review these generated baseline inputs when present:\n31: \n32: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-discovery.md`\n33: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/plan-seed.md`\n34: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/plan-seed.json`\n35: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-feature-survey.md`\n36: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-file-inventory.md`\n37: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-coverage-matrix.md`\n38: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-coverage-matrix-report.md`\n39: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/verification-results.md`\n40: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\phase-task-checklist.md` when a phase session is running\n41: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/platform-capability-check.md`\n42: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/platform-capability-check-report.md`\n43: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/target-structure-report.md`\n44: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/resource-coverage-report.md`\n45: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/coverage-gap-report.md`\n46: \n47: Then inspect relevant files from the unified inventory:\n48: \n49: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-discovery.json`\n50: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-discovery.md`\n51: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/mapcir/*.mapcir.json`\n52: